Festivo Agent Rules (Always Apply)

1) Mandatory context loading before every task
- Before any analysis, coding, or command execution, read these files in this exact order:
  1. PROJECT_CONTEXT.md
  2. AI_CONTEXT.md
  3. AI_DEVELOPER_RULES.md
  4. AI_SYSTEM_ARCHITECT.md
  5. docs/database-schema.md
  6. docs/system-architecture.md
  7. docs/notification-system.md
  8. docs/er-diagram.md
- Do not skip this step, even for small tasks.

2) Automatic context/documentation synchronization after every completed task
- After every completed task, update the relevant source-of-truth docs automatically, without asking the user.
- Always evaluate whether each of these needs an update:
  - PROJECT_CONTEXT.md
  - AI_CONTEXT.md
  - docs/database-schema.md
  - docs/system-architecture.md
  - docs/notification-system.md
  - docs/er-diagram.md
- If no update is needed for a specific file, leave it unchanged.
- If schema, architecture, API behavior, jobs, or notification flow changed, docs must be updated in the same task.

3) Short project architecture summary
- Festivo is a moderation-first festival platform.
- Public users read from `festivals` (verified/published scope).
- Ingestion writes candidate data into `pending_festivals`.
- Admin reviews pending records and approves/rejects in `/app/admin`.
- Approve creates/updates canonical public data and preserves moderation traceability.
- Supabase Postgres + RLS is the persistent source of truth.
- Notification flow: user plan/reminder/follow events -> `user_notifications` -> push delivery via `device_tokens`.

4) Coding conventions
- Prefer small, incremental changes over broad refactors.
- Reuse existing patterns in `app/api`, `app/admin/api`, `lib/*`.
- Keep TypeScript types explicit and aligned with existing project types.
- Do not introduce dependencies unless required.
- Keep server-only privileged logic on server routes/functions.
- Preserve API compatibility unless a breaking change is explicitly requested.
- Add/adjust tests and docs when behavior changes.

5) Database rules (strict)
- Never modify database schema directly from app code.
- Never assume schema changes exist in runtime environments.
- Schema changes are allowed only via SQL migration files in `scripts/sql/`.
- Use migration naming format: `YYYYMMDD_description.sql`.
- Include required indexes/constraints/RLS policy updates when relevant.
- Do not drop tables/columns or perform destructive data changes without explicit user approval.

6) Post-task auto-update requirement (non-interactive)
- After each finished task, automatically sync the following docs when impacted:
  - PROJECT_CONTEXT.md
  - AI_CONTEXT.md
  - docs/database-schema.md
  - docs/system-architecture.md
  - docs/notification-system.md
  - docs/er-diagram.md
- Do this without prompting the user.
